        a: '<b>No.</b> TypeScript is <b><u>statically typed</u></b> — types are checked at <u>compile time</u>, not runtime.<br/><br/>At runtime, TypeScript compiles to plain JavaScript, which <u>IS dynamically typed</u>. TypeScript\'s types are completely <u>erased</u> during compilation.<br/><br/><pre class="bg-gray-800 text-gray-100 p-3 rounded-lg mt-2 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>// TypeScript (compile time)\nlet name: string = "Alice";\nname = 123;  // ❌ Compile ERROR: Type \'number\' not assignable to \'string\'\n\n// After compilation → JavaScript (runtime)\nlet name = "Alice";\nname = 123;  // ✅ No error at runtime — types are gone\n\n// Type assertions don\'t change runtime behavior\nconst input = document.getElementById("name") as HTMLInputElement;\n// At runtime, this is just: document.getElementById("name")\n\n// \'any\' opts out of type checking\nlet data: any = "hello";\ndata = 42;       // No error\ndata = { x: 1 }; // No error</code></pre>',
